05758nam a22007815i 9780292762817DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211978txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927628177 a10.7560/7503952doi  a(DE-B1597)587292  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPQ8498.32.A65bZ715 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a86322300aMario Vargas Llosa :bA Collection of Critical Essays /ced. by Charles Rossman, Alan Warren Friedman. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1978  a1 online resource (194 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tEditors' Preface -- t"Of how to be and what to see while you are being": The Reader's Performance in The Time of the Hero -- tA Small Whirlpool: Narrative Structure in The Green House -- tThe Sources of The Green House: The Mythical Background of a Fabulous Novel -- tMario Vargas Llosa and Conversation in The Cathedral: The Question of Naturalism -- tConversations and Confessions: Self and Character in The Fall and Conversation in The Cathedral -- tThe Narrative Art of Mario Vargas Llosa: Two Organizing Principles in Pantaleon y las visitadoras -- tApollo's Metamorphosis in Pantaleón y las visitadoras -- tA City Boy -- tVargas Llosa, the Novelist as a Critic -- tMario Vargas Llosa and the Totalization Impulse -- tMario Vargas Llosa: A Labyrinth of Solitude -- tMario Vargas Llosa: The Necessary Scapegoat -- tConversacio'n con Mario Vargas Llosa sobre La tía Julia y el escribidor -- tLa tía Julia y el escribidor, or the Coded Self-Portrait -- tA Mario Vargas Llosa Chronology -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Peruvian Mario Vargas Llosa has been acclaimed throughout the literary world as one of Latin America's finest writers, yet until recently little has been written about his work in English. While his work has the subject of an increasing flow of critical commentary in Spanish and his major novels have been translated into English, this is the first full-scale critical treatment of Vargas Llosa published in the English language. These articles by a number of established writers and critics appraise Vargas Llosa's individual novels as well as the body of his work. The Time of the Hero, The Green House, Conversation in The Cathedral, and Pantaleón y las visitadoras are examined in order of publication, A second group of more general essays ranges across Vargas Llosa's work and explores pervasive themes and concerns. Two pieces by José Miguel Oviedo serve as a coda. In a bilingual interview, Oviedo and Vargas Llosa discuss Vargas Llosa's novel La tía Julia y el escribidor. Oviedo concludes with a critical discussion of that novel. A Vargas Llosa chronology compiled by the editors is also included. Most of these essays originally appeared in 1977 as a special issue of Texas Studies in Literature and Language. The concluding essay by Oviedo was prepared especially for this edition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAuthors, Spanish. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Rilda L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrody, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheuse, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDíez, Luys A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeustle, Joseph A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiler, Malva E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranco, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela